{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_archylee_ver01/data/sn82016196/00516992438/1949010601/0003.xml":{"full_text":"Negro History Week Theme, Feb. 6,\n'History as it Should Be Taught'\nPosters for the 24th annual\ncelebration of Negro History\nWeek, carrying the theme \u201cHis\ntory as it should be taught,\u201d are\nnow being distributed free of\ncharge. Likewise sample copies\nof The Negro History Bulletin\nwhich give valuable information\nas to how to make the celebra\ntion count. The Negro History\nWeek Kit, however containing\nrecitations, declarations, a play,\nprograms for each day of the\nweek, and sentence sketches of\nall prominent Negroes, sells for\n$2.00.\nThe theme of the celebration\nIs taken from the words of James\nWeldon Johnson. Before he left\nFlorida to rise to fame as a writ\ner and reformer in the New York\narea he had rendered outstand\ning service as a teacher and prin\ncipal of the Stanton High School\nin Jacksonville. He lamented the\nfact that in the teaching of his\ntory in our schools the story of\nthe Negro is omitted. He decided\nto do something about it. He\nwrote books dramatizing the\nstrivings of the Negro upward.\nHis Black Manhattan is an im\nportant chapter in the history of\nthe Negro in the United States.\nSpeaking more expliciy about\nthe need for a change in our\nmethod of teaching history, he\nsaid:\n\u201cTake history as it is common\nly taught in our schools. It is\ntaught from a textbook that com\npletely ignores he Negro or\nmentions him only in conde\nscending or derogatory terms.\nThat is a bad sort of history to\nteach to white youth; when it is\ntaught to Negro youth it is ab\nsolutely pernicious.\nThe fact is, there is hardly an\nImportant page of American his\ntory that can be fully and truth\nfully written without reference\nto the Negro as a contributing\nfactor. Then, for Negro youth to\nstudy American history and learn\nnothing of the part played by\nthe Negro Americans in the mak\ning of that history is an absurd\nity. Notwithstanding, it is pathet\nically true that there are thous\nands of Negro youth in our\nHELEN OF TROY WOULD BE ENVIOUS OF THIS\nTHE SENSATIONAL 1949 SALE AT THE\nVICTOR CLOTHING COMPANY\nLittle as $3.00 down and $3.00 weekly,\nbuys you up to SIOO worth of\nAmerica's finest clothes.\nYes, this Fabulous gal launched a thousand ships, but\nwhen the chips are down for the clothes you need it\u2019s\nLeo Sunshine Fon-a-row at the good Victor Clothing\na- Company, 214 S. Broadway, down-\ntown Los Angeles where you\nset sail for the most amazing values\n^e year. Famous Bronson suits j^.\ns all wool blacks, blues, bankers\ngrey anc Y ou these with\nt out interest oxford grey, and\nyou don\u2019t have to go to Harvard to\nthem. And those famous Bronson\ntuxedos. All these priced from S3O\nKHHh Ww\u00dfto SIOO in one-button, two-button, J^-\nsemi-full drapes and you can\nbutton up all you clothing problems\nwhen you shop this sensational ad-\nventure in dress up joy. Open your account in less\n-K than 5 minutes Paul Revere never did it any\nquicker WE GIVE CREDIT TO EVERYONE AND\nCREDIT IS FREE! Open Monday thru Friday til 6\u2014\nSaturday nights til 9\u2014Park Free Next Door.\n\nCTO fl CIOWIMG CO,\n214 SOUTH BROADWAY\n-A Jr\nDOWNTOWN LOS ANGELES\nA- lee \"Sunshine\" Fon-a-row 14-\n^*l* bn\nManager and Stockholder\nStore hours 9-6 daily. (Open every Saturday night \u2019til 9)\n44*444444444\nBROADWAY FEDERAL SAVINGS AND LOAN\nASSOCIATION OF LOS ANGELES\nSTATEMENT OF CONDITION, DECEMBER 31. IMS\nASSETS LIABILITIES\nLoans on Real Estate $1,504,337.85 Investment Shares $1,075,459.49\nInterest Receivable 577.79 Dividends on Investment Shares 13,440.03\nLoans Secured by Shares of Advances from Federal Home\nthe Association 1,320.00 Loan Bank J73 ,325.00\nFederal Hopie Lun Bank Stock 22.400.00 Miscellaneous Liabilities 1.W.1\u00bb\nCash on Hand and in Banks 40,539.15 RESERVES AND SURPLUS\nFurniture, Fixtures and Specific Reserve 577.79\nEquipment EUMIIIIiIIItoB 11,029.27 Federal Insurance Reserve 13,800.00\nMiscellaneous Assets 4,434.80 Undivided Profits 23,324.06\nTotal $1,584,638.86 Total $1,584,638.86\nMember of:\nFEDERAL HOME LOAM BANK SYSTEM, FEDERAL INSURANCE CORPORATION,\nUNITED STATES SAVINGS AND LOAN LEAGUE, NATIONAL SAVINGS AND\nLOAN LEAGUE, CALIFORNIA SAVINGS AND LOAN LEAGUE, AMERICAN SAV\nINGS AND LOAN LEAGUE.\nschools and colleges who have\nnever read the life of Frederick\nDouglass or of Booker T. Wash\nington; to whom Nat Turner and\nDenmark Vesey and Sojourner\nTruth and Harriet Tubman are\nnot even names.\nThese young people have noth\ning to stand on. They have no\nground under their feet. It is idle\nto talk to them about race pride,\nwhen they know of nothing of\nwhich to be proud. Race pride\ncannot be pumped into them ar\ntificially, it must spring natural\nly from their knowledge of all\nthat is best in racial history,\nand must rest upon a resulting\nfaith in the strength and capac\nities of the race. Without this\nknowledge and faith they are\nsuspended, and when the forces\nof prejudice strike them they\nhave nothing to fall back on.\nKnowledge of the extraordi\nnary history of the race in this\ncountry and of the men and wo\nmen who have achieved high\nmarks in that history is essen\ntial to them as a sustaining\nforce. Such pride of race as this\nwill not make them lesser but\nbetter American citizens; it will\nnot tend to separate them from\nthe national life but will make\nthem a stronger component part\nof it.\u201d\nThis celebration marks also\nthe 33rd year of the Association\nfor the Study of Negro Life and\nHistory. The organization was\nlaunched September 9, 1915 in\nChicago by Carter G. Woodson\nand four others cooperating with\nhim in the undertaking. The or\nganization brought out The\nJournal of Negro History in Jan\nuary, 1916 and has published it\nregularly every quarter since. In\n1926 the Association launched\nthe celebration of Negro History\nWeek. In 1937 the Association be,\ngan the publication of The Negro\nHistory Bulletin to popularize\nand give a new interpretation of\nNegro History Week as an occa\nsion for demonstrating what the\nschools and clubs have achieved\nby studying the Negro through\nout the year.\nC. G. Woodson\nUrban League\nHit Hard By\nMoney Lack\nThe National Urban League is\nreporting on its financial ex\nperiences during 1948 and the\neffect of those experiences on\nits plans for 1949 in a frank\nstatement to its members and\nto the general public. The state\nment was issued following the\npublication of the League\u2019s End\nof-the-Year Summary of activi\nties entitled \u201cAn American\nStory.\u201d Similar summaries have\nreached League members and\ncontributors each year during\nthe past 38 years.\nLeague officials warned the\nmembership that staff opera\ntions and program activities\nmust be reduced in 1949 because\nof the National Urban League\u2019s\nfailure to reach the financial\ngoal set in its 1948 campaign.\nTraffic Signal\nOperating Soon\n\u201cNew traffic signals will be\ninstalled at 51st and Central,\u201d\naccording to Council Kenneth\nHahn.\nThey will give better protec\ntion to pedestrians crossing this\nbusy street and will slow down\nthe fast drivers on Central ave.\nCouncilman Hahn expects the\nsignals to be installed within\nten days.\nSuper Clerk to Be\nElected in Super Store\nThe Super Liquor stores of Los\nAngeles are staging a contest to\nelect the \u201cSuper Clerk\u201d of 1949.\nThe clerk, a man or woman, who\nreceives the highest number of\nvotes will be given this title.\nBallot boxes are set up in each\nstore, and everyone is urged to\nvote for his favorite clerk. Con\ntest closes midnight, February\n28, 1949.\nBenny and Rochester\nHOLLYWOOD (Atlas News\nService) \u2014Eddie (Rochester) An\nderson will do at least a week\u2019s\nstand of personal appearances\nwith Jack Benny this summer.\nBenny will leave for London\nafter an engagement at Boston\nin June. It is not known wheth\ner Phil Harris and Rochester, who\nwas with him last summer, will\nmake the trip to London.\nGUUHUa highest\nWITH THE SAME\nsvmu semen\nNtAmt\nZa SBk X CRAIG STATION\n(CRAIG) a\nEGYPTIAN TEMPLE Number Five, elevated Noble Louis H.\nJones to the position of Potentate for 1949. The meeting\nof the Nobles of Egyptian Temple at which the elevation\ntook place was held last month. Noble Jones, succeeds\nNoble Arthur Quarles, who now becomes a Past Potentate.\nNoble Quarles who is also a Past Master and a Past Grand\nOfficer in the Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of\nCalifornia, F and AM, was a representative at the Impeial\nCouncil\u2019s 47th annual convention in St. Louis. He brought\na national champion patrol team back to Egyptian Temple.\nPast Potentate Quarles, left is shown above congratulating\nIllustrious Potentate Jones.\nEnough Labor For Crop Work\nThe Department of Employ\nment reports that there is more\nthan adequate labor to meet the\ncoming harvest labor needs. The\ncotton harvest is about 85 per\ncent complete, and many pick\ners are going home to other coun\nties or other states.\nCitrus areas report that the\nrain will improve the size of\nNavel oranges and lemons. Ex\nperienced citrus packers will be\nin demand by early February.\nThe Central Coast vegetable\nharvest includes artichokes,\nBrussels sprouts and cauliflower.)\nThe peak of orchard and vine\nyard pruning is not expected un\ntil January and February, and\nthere is an adequate labor sup\nply of experienced pruners.\nThe normal seasonal decline in\nagricultural employment is being\nspeeded up somewhat by weath\ner conditions. A sharp drop in\nthe cotton harvest employment\nwas caused by heavy fog and\na severe dust storm in the San\nJoaquin Valley.\nKress Strike\n(Continued From Page 1)\ncalled as the jurist who sent\nJoseph DeSilva, secretary of\nretail clerks local 770, to jail\nfor peaceful picketing before a\ndrug store. His decision was\nunanimously reversed by the\nCalifornia Supreme Court.\nIn this instance, Judge Hanson\nsigned the restraining order at\nthe behest of Kress attorney, J.\nStuart Neary, without permitting\nattorneys or representatives of\nthe Retail Clerks Union to ex\npress themselves in the matter.\nRobert W. Gilbert, attorney for\nthe Retail Clerks International\nhad requested two weeks pre\nviously that he be heard in the\nevent an application for injunc\ntion was made to the court. He\nwas not notified and the order\nwas issued after only the em\nployer\u2019s side had been presented.\nCommenting on the one\nsided order. Retail Clerks In\nternational Organizer, Paul.\nHanson said it is possible that\nthe reaction of the Los An\ngeles labor movement, under\nthe circumstances, would be\nthe same as that which came\nabout when the Merchants and\nManufacturers Associated cre\nated a state of emergency here\nin 1946 under the unconstitu\ntional hot cargo act.\nUnusual Offer\nIn FHA Homes\nA builder offers the last of\ntitle 6 F.H.A. homes. They are\nunusual and two bedroom homes,\nrecently completed, beautifully\nlandscaped. They are built with\npre-war material and plumbing\nfixtures and hardwood floors.\nOutstanding feature. $39 per mo.\nSee General Building Co., 359 S.\nRobinson blvd., Beverly Hills.\nBR. 2-5000.\nThe 39th North American Es\nperanto Congress was held in To\nronto, Canada, in July, 1948.\n\"SEEING IS BELIEVING\"\nCALIFORNIA'S LARGEST AND USED RUG STORE\nNEW BROADLOOM\n12', 15', 18' WIDTHS\nM 95\nMl sq. yd.\nfrom up\nFrom Looms of Alexander Smith Sona\nMohawk, Firth, Gulistan Magee\nMohawk, Firth, Gulistan A Magee\nPlain, Figured and Carved\n\u201cFOR LOW BUDGET NEEDS\u2019*\n1,000 USED RUGS: 6x9, 7',2x9. Bxlo,\n9x12, 9x15, 11x15, 12x18, 12x24, etc.\nCLEAN AND READY TO USE\nBUDGET TERMS AVAILABLE\nSINGER'S RUG CARPET CO.\n1487 Sunset Blvd. MU. 4522\nOPEN WED. EVE. TILL 9 P.M.\nByron Hanna\nHeads Drive\nThe Young Men\u2019s Christian\nAssociation of Los Angeles has\nannounced that Byron C. Hanna,\nprominent attorney here, will\nserve as General Chairman for\nits 1949 Current Support Fund\nCampaign which has a goal of\n$600,000 to meet the budgetary\nneeds of the twenty-two branches\nthroughout the area.\nIn accepting the post, Mr.\nHanna, a member of the law\nfirm of Hanna Morton, said,\n\u201cI consider the Y.M.C.A. pro\ngram one which deserves the\nsupport of every right-thinking\nAmerican, since the youth of our\nnation represent the backbone\nof our future.\u201d\nMore Benefits\nFor December\nState disability insurance bene\nfits increased in December when\n$398,907 of the greater Los An\ngeles district total of $626,464\nwere paid to 8,703 Los Angeles\nworkers who were temporarily\nunable to work, due to off-time\njob illness or injury, William R.\nDougherty, manager of the Los\nAngeles Disability Insurance Of\nfice of the Department of Em\nployment announced this week.\nDuring the previous month a\ntotal of $368,262 was paid to\n8,231 workers.\nSpeaks On Credit\nPossible effects upon both\nshort and long-term credit in\n1949 of financial trends since\nVJ Day will be the subject of\nPreident C. E. Earhart of the\nFederal Reserve Bank of San\nFrancisco when he speaks at a\nbusiness outlook conference be\ning staged January 20 by the\nLos Angeles Chamber of Com\nmerce.\nVisiting Here\n(NPB)\u2014Mrs. Annie L.\nForester of New York City and\nwife of Dr. Joseph Forester,\nprominent dentist, arriver here\nfor a vacation visit with several\nof her relatives. Arriving with\nMrs. Forester, was Miss Della\nFrye, also of New York.\nWhile in the city, Mrs.\nForester will be the houseguest\nof her cousin, Arthur F. Adams\nSr. of 9418 Bandero street. The\nNew Yorker is aso the cousin\nof Albert Echols retired Los An\ngeles police officer. Many at\ntractive and interesting affairs\nare being planned in the visior\u2019s\nhonor.\nNo Complaint Here\nLos Angeles county will have\na windfall of $4,256,077 as a re\nsult of the state taking over\nadministration of aged and blind\naid on January 1, under the\nterms of Prop. No. 4 (Article\nXXV, California Constitution),\nCalifornia Taxpayers\u2019 1 associa\ntion estimated today.\nW. C. Handy Relates\nStory of His Own Life\nMEMPHIS, Tenn.\u2014W. C. Han\ndy. \u201cFather of the Blues\u201d and\nmusic publisher, spoke to the\nstudents at Bt. Augustine\u2019s\nschool here recently. The au\nthor of the \"Saint Louis Blues,\u201d\nHandy recounted various inci\ndents from his own life.\nSt. Augustine\u2019s school, which is\nconducted, by the Sisters of Char\nity, a CafhbHc Sisterhood, has\nmore than 500 students enrolled.\nSome Left Anyhow\nState Gov't Cost\nSACRAMENTO California\u2019s\nGeneral Fund cash excess over\ncurrent obligations on November\n30 amounted to $119,139,945, ac\ncording to a statement released\nby State Controller Thomas H.\nKuchel.\nThe California Eagle, Thursday, January 6,1949\u2014\nPost Office Record Receipts\nPostal receipts of the Los An\ngeles Post Office for 1948 hit a\nnew peak, and this city is run\nning a close race for third high\nspot honors in the United States,\naccording to Postmaster Michael\nYour Business\nLicense Fee is\nPayable Now!\nApproximately 122,000 business\nand professional men have re\nceived reminders in the mail\nsince January Ist that their an\nnual city busineses license fees\nare now due.\nCity Clark Walter C. Peterson\njurges all persons or firms to\nforward their remittances by\nmail as early as possible so that\nthe issuance of licenses may be\nexpedited.\nEvery effort has been made\nto enable business firms to re\nnew their licenses by mail. All\nthe necessary information is on\nthe renewal notices and a self\naddressed envelope Is enclosed\nfor convenience.\nTo complete payment, 11 is\nnecessary that the notice be\nsigned and returned by mail\nwith a check.\nMake checks payable and ad\ndress all communications to\nWalter C. Peterson, City Clerk,\nRoom 1, City Hall, Los Angeles\n12. Telephone information is\navailable on Michigan 5211, Ex\ntension 2421.\nA 10% penalty will be added if\nfees are not paid by 5:00 p.m.,\nFebruary 28, 1946, 5% addi\ntional penalty will be added on\nthe last day of each calendar\nmonth thereafter until 50% is\nadded.\nBranch offices will also be\nalso opened during the renewal\nperiod.\nPres. Truman\n(Continued From Page 1)\noppose this last measure. But on\nthe other hand, the Progressive\n(Republicans in Congress have\npledged themselves to work with\nthe Progressive Democrats for\nthe things President Truman has\nasked.\nThe Administration has al\nready won a victory. When the\n81st Congress met to organize\nlast Monday, they changed the\nrule of the Rules Committee.\nThis is the committee which de\ncides whgt and when a bill shall\nbe presented to the floor of the\nHouse. Hitherto there was no lim\nit to the time it could hold up\nneeded legislation, and many a\ngood biJi was choked to death in\nthe committee.\nThe House of- the 81st Congress\ndecided Monday the Rules Com\nmittee could not hold a bill long\ner than 21 days, when it would\nautomatically be released upon\nthe demand of its author.\nAn active Esperanto Club has\nbeen formed in the Missouri\nSchool of Mines, among the stu\ndents and professors with the\napproval of the University.\nOPRINCE\nHAIR DRESSING\nImproved OPRINCE\nmake* the worst\nform of Stubborn\nHair slick down\nstraight at once for f\ndays It's not gum*\nmy. Keeps the hair\nStrato through\nsweat. 'Xtra big\ncan Ue and Me. i- >a W\nAt Drag Stores and\nBarber Shops and fefe \u2019WI\nSe and 10c stores.\nOr write Golden \\WTjsg^'~jX/\nState Toilet Products. 'wS^^^SFy\nStation K. Boi IM. vVy/\nta\u00ab Aneeies Calif.\nDR. GAY\nCREDIT DENTIST\nTHE FAMILY CREDIT DENTIST\nOPEN EVENINGS\n20 th Anniversary\nNO APPOINTMENT NECESSARY\nDental Plates\nOne Day Plate Service\nImmediate Restorations\nExtration of Teeth and Mouth Preparation for Partlab\nand Full Dentures\nPartial Dentures and Removable Bridgework\nPlates Repaired While You Wait\nEASY CREDIT\nALWAYS LOW PRICES\nNew Hours 9 A.M. to 9 P.M.\nDR. GAY, Credit Dentist\nCORNER VERNON and CENTRAL AVE.\nCE. 2-1397\nD. Fanning.\nHe stated that the final re\nceipt figure for the year will ap\nproximate $32,456,261, which is\na 12.48 percent increase over\n1947. In comparison with pre\nvious years the Postmaster men\ntioned that only 10 years ago,\nin 1938, the receipts were $12,-\n924,843.23.\nThe estimated $4,024,769 re\nceived from the sale of stamps\nduring the month of December\nthis year will be about the tamp\nas the total receipts for the year\nof 1920.\nFanning said letter and card\ncancellations will show a 10 per\ncent increase over last year, with\nparcel post figures advancing\nabout 20 percent more than 1947.\nThe Postmaster stated that\nseveral new postal stations are\nbeing planned to take care of\nthe increased postal business in\nthe city. In addition, he. an\nnounced that plans are now pro\ngressing to add a new story to\nthe Terminal Annex working\npost office.\nMake Your Own\nWaffle Syrup\nFor those hot griddle eakes\nand waffles, so welcome on cold\nwinter mornings, a sirup made\nwith cup com syrup; cup\nwater and 1 cup sugar\u2014 stirred\nand heated together\u2014 is suggest\ned by the U. S. Department of\nAgriculture. Although appetlz\ningly thick, this syrup does not\ncrystallize on standing as many\nother syrups do. Thus, it may\nbe made in advance and kept in\nthe refrigerator to serve cold\nor heated, as preferred.\nCom syrup is one of the corn\nproducts now plentiful on mar\nkets as a result of the last great\ncorn crop. Its flavor Is less\nsweet than sugar.\n200,000\nworth of\nFine Furs\nto be sold for\n75 r OOO\nWe are certain these val\nues cannot be duplicated\nanywhere wholesale\nor retail\nCOATS\nCAPES\nSTOLES\n\nMoney back\nGuarantee\nRUS KOLINSKY\nSKINS\n>750\nEach\nWere $20.00\nUse Our Lay-Awey Plan\nSPELLMAN'S\nExclusive Furs\n706 SO. HILL ST.\nsth Floor\nCutts Bldg.\nTRinity 0255\n3","height":"30972","width":"22388"}}
